Cell.Data: Usually, this is used for documents other than those defined by FHIR

Document identifier as assigned by the source of the document. This identifier is specific to this version of the document. This unique identifier may be used elsewhere to identify this version of the document
Other identifiers associated with the record

Who or what the document is about. The document can be about a person, (patient or healthcare practitioner), a device (I.e. machine) or even a group of subjects (such as a document about a herd of farm animals, or a set of patients that share a common exposure)
PID-3-Patient ID List (No standard way to define a Practitioner or Group subject in V2 MDM message)
What kind of document this is (LOINC if possible)
Specifies the particular kind of document (e.g. Patient Summary, Discharge Summary, Prescription, etc.)
Key metadata element describing the document, used in searching/filtering.
More detail about the document type
More detailed information about the document type
Identifies who is responsible for adding the information to the document
Not necessarily who did the actual data entry (i.e. typist) it in or who was the source (informant)
TXA-9-Originator Code/Name (No standard way to indicate a Device in V2 MDM message)
Identifies the organization or group who is responsible for ongoing maintenance of and access to the document
Identifies where to go to find the current version, where to report issues, etc.
Which person or organization authenticates that this document is valid
Creation time is used for tracking, organizing versions and searching. This is the creation time of the document, not the source material on which it is based
When the document reference was created
Referencing/indexing time is used for tracking, organizing versions and searching.
The status of this document reference
The status of the underlying document
Human Readable description of the source document. This is sometimes known as the "title"
Helps humans to assess whether the document is of interest

What the document is about, rather than a terse summary of the document. It's commonly the case that records do not have a title and are collectively referred to by the display name of Record code (e.g. a "consultation" or "progress note").
A code specifying the level of confidentiality of the XDS Document

The interpretation of this field, and more generally enforcement and issues related to highly sensitive documents are beyond the scope of this resource. confidentialityCode can only be understood in the context of the policies, procedures, and value set specified by the context in which the document reference is being used
The primary language in which the source document is written
The mime type of the source document
Note: application/hl7-v3+xml for CDA. application/binary for proprietary record formats
The format of the document. This is used when the mimeType of the document does not provide enough differentiating information (typically, when the mime type of the document is text/xml)
Size of the document in bytes
The size of the source document this reference refers to in bytes
A hash of the source document to ensure that changes have not occurred
Whether the hash must be present and/or correct depends on the document handling rules defined in the context of use
A url at which the document can be accessed
(Might include V2 TXA-16-Unique Document File Name or TXA-24-Folder Assignment)
If access is not fully described by location
A description of a service call that can be used to retrieve the document
If a document can be accessed by either a service or directly by a URL (i.e. an XDS repository with an MHD access point, or a DICOM network with a WADO portal) just provide the URL
The type of the service that can be used to access the documents
The meaning and interpretation of the parameters depends on the service type
Where service is located (usually a URL)
Where the service end-point is located
Usually this is a URL, but for some services, the end-point is a simple network name or address that is not a valid URL
A list of named parameters that is used in the service call
The interpretation of the parameters, and how to convert them into a proper service call, is dependent on the type of the service, and needs to be specified in an implementation guide somewhere
The value of the named parameter
The clinical context in which the document was prepared
These values are primarily added to help with searching for interesting/relevant documents
Type of context (i.e. type of event)
The type of clinical context, such as a kind of surgery, or a kind of speciality, or a clinical type
The time period of the patient's care that is described by the document
Kind of facility where patient was seen
The kind of facility where the patient was seen
A location or a service (or both) must be provided
The status of the document reference
This is the current reference for this document
This reference has been superseded by another reference
This reference was created in error
